    <h2 id="Adding-Analytics">Adding Analytics</h2>
    <p>
      There are two ways to include analytics in your Web Stories:
    </p>

    <ul class="real-ul">
      <li>Add your Google Analytics ID in the "Editor Settings".
      <li>If you use the <a href="https://sitekit.withgoogle.com/">Site Kit by Google WordPress</a> plugin, you can set up Web Story analytics there.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <b>Note</b>: Site Kit and Tag Manager do not yet work together. <a href="https://github.com/google/site-kit-wp/issues/2070">Follow progress here</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Web Stories for WordPress includes the following default analytics events:
    </p>
    <ul class="real-ul">
      <li><strong>Story Progress:</strong> Fired when a story page becomes visible.</li>
      <li><strong>Story End:</strong> Fired when the last story page displays to the user. This can be used to measure completion rate.</li>
      <li><strong>Track Focus State:</strong> Fired when clicking an element that opens a tooltip such as an `<a>` link or twitter embed.</li> 
      <li><strong>Story Open:</strong> Fired when opening a drawer or dialog inside a story, such as a page attachment.</li>
      <li><strong>Story Close:</strong> Fired when closing a drawer or dialog inside a story, such as a page attachment.</li>
      <li><strong>Audio Muted:</strong> Fired when the user initiates an interaction to mute the audio for the current story.</li>
      <li><strong>Audio Unmuted:</strong> Fired when the user initiates an interaction to unmute the audio for the current story.</li>
      <li><strong>Page Attachment Enter:</strong> Fired when a user opens a page attachment.</li>
      <li><strong>Page Attachment Exit:</strong> Fired when a user closes a page attachment.</li>
      <li><strong>Story Bookend Enter:</strong> Fired when the the story displays the bookend to the user, after the last page of the current story.</li>
      <li><strong>Story Bookend Exit:</strong> Fired when the user dismisses the bookend.</li>
    </ul>
